'''Suicide''' is when a person chooses to kill himself or herself. The word suicide is from the [[Latin]] words ''sui caedere'', which means "to kill oneself". In English, when someone kills himself, people say that he has "committed suicide," or "suicided." Doctors consider suicide attempts to be a symptom of a serious [[Depression (illness)|depression]]. Suicide is a [[crime]] in some places,<ref>{{Cite web
 |url= http://www.vakilno1.com/bareacts/IndianPenalCode/S309.htm
 |title=Laws - IPC - Section 309
 |work=vakilno1.com
 |accessdate=April 5, 2010
}}</ref> and it is considered a [[sin]] in many [[religion]]s.<ref>{{Cite web
 |url= http://www.inter-islam.org/Prohibitions/suicide.html
 |title=Suicide as seen in Islam
 |work=inter-islam.org
 |accessdate=April 5, 2010
}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web
 |url= http://www.hinduwebsite.com/hinduism/h_suicide.asp
 |title=Hinduism and suicide
 |work=hinduwebsite.com
 |accessdate=April 5, 2010
}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web
 |url= http://www.religionfacts.com/euthanasia/judaism.htm
 |title=Euthanasia and Judaism: Jewish Views of Euthanasia and Suicide - ReligionFacts
 |work=religionfacts.com
 |accessdate=April 5, 2010
}}</ref><ref>{{citebook|title=The Catholic Encyclopedia|last=Vander Heeren|first=Achille|chapter=Suicide|volume=14|location=New York|publisher=Robert Appleton Company|year=1912|url=http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/14326b.htm}}</ref>
==Risk factors==
[[File:Suicide-risk factors-protective factors.PNG|thumb|Examples of suicide risk and protective factors.<br><small>Source: 2012 National Strategy for Suicide Prevention</small>]]
===Mental disorders===   
Many people who commit suicide have a [[Mental illness|mental disorder]], the rates vary according to study between 85%-95%. Depressive disorders account for about 80% of these numbers, schizophrenia 10% and dementia and delirium about 5%. Among those who have a mental disorder, 25% also have alcohol abuse issues. People who abuse alcohol have a 50% greater risk of suicide comapred to those who do not.<ref> Benjamin James Sadock, M.D., Virginia Alcott Sadock: Kapalan and Sadock's Concise Textbook of Clinical Psychiatry.  Lippincott Williams & Wilkins; Third edition (2008) ISBN 0781787467</ref>

While acts of [[self-harm]] are not considered as suicide attempts, the presence of self-harming behavior may increase the risk of suicide.<ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 17606825 | doi=10.1001/archpedi.161.7.634 | volume=161 | issue=7 | title=The relationship between self-injurious behavior and suicide in a young adult population | year=2007 | month=July | author=Whitlock J, Knox KL | journal=Arch Pediatr Adolesc Med | pages=634–40}}</ref>
====Emotions====
'''Hopelessness''': the feeling that there is no prospect of improvement in one's situation---is a strong indicator of suicide.<ref>American Psychiatric Association: American Psychiatric Association Practice Guidelines for the Treatment of Psychiatric Disorders: Compendium 2006. American Psychiatric Publishing; 1 edition (2006) pp.1410-1411 ISBN 0890423857</ref>
<p> 
'''Perceived burdensomeness''': when a person feels that they are a burden to others such as one's family, is often coupled with hopelessness<ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 20967639 | doi=10.1080/13607863.2010.501064 | volume=15 | issue=2 | title=The mediating effect of perceived burdensomeness on the relation between depressive symptoms and suicide ideation in a community sample of older adults | year=2011 | month=March | author=Jahn DR, Cukrowicz KC, Linton K, Prabhu F | journal=Aging Ment Health | pages=214–20}}</ref> 
<p>
'''Loneliness''': whether a person just feels lonely or they actually are alone. A lack of social support such as family and friends, a feeling of not belonging or fitting in, and living alone.<ref>{{Cite pmid|21142333}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 11326767 | volume=31 | issue=1 | title=Loneliness in relation to suicide ideation and parasuicide: a population-wide study | year=2001 | author=Stravynski A, Boyer R | journal=Suicide Life Threat Behav | pages=32–40}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 16214699 | doi=10.1080/13607860500193062 | volume=9 | issue=6 | title=Social relationships as predictors of depression and suicidal ideation in older adults | year=2005 | month=November | author=Vanderhorst RK, McLaren S | journal=Aging Ment Health | pages=517–25}}</ref>
====Substance abuse====
Substance abuse is the second most common [[Factor (medicine)|risk factor]] for suicide after [[major depressive disorder]] and [[bipolar disorder]].<ref>{{Cite book |last1=D., PhD Frank |first1=Jerome |last2=Levin |first2=Jerome D |last3=S., PhD Piccirilli |first3=Richard |last4=Perrotto |first4=Richard S |last5=Culkin |first5=Joseph |title=Introduction to chemical dependency counseling |url=http://books.google.com/?id=felzn3Ntd-cC&pg=RA1-PA151 |date=28 Sep 2001 |publisher=Jason Aronson |location=Northvale, NJ |isbn=978-0-7657-0289-0 |pages=150–152}}</ref> Both chronic substance misuse as well as acute substance abuse are associated with suicide.<ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 17458329 | volume=19 | issue=1 | title=Psychological autopsy studies: the role of alcohol use in adolescent and young adult suicides | year=2007 | author=Giner L, Carballo JJ, Guija JA, ''et al.'' | journal=Int J Adolesc Med Health | pages=99–113}}</ref>   When combined with personal grief, the risk of suicide is greatly increased.<ref name=behavioral_science_in_medicine>{{Cite book |last=Fadem |first=Barbara |url= http://books.google.com/?id=KB-g-oBfApsC |title=Behavioral science in medicine |date=1 Dec 2003 |publisher=Lippincott Williams Wilkins |location=Philadelphia |isbn= 978-0-7817-3669-5 |page=217}}</ref> More than 50% of suicides have some relation to alcohol or drug use and up to 25% of suicides are committed by drug addicts and alcoholics, among adolescents, it is as high as 70%. 
