! scope="row" | [[Alcohol]]
| Alcohol misuse is associated with a number of mental health disorders, and alcoholics have a very high suicide rate. Suicide from alcoholism is more common in older adults.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Chignon JM, Cortes MJ, Martin P, Chabannes JP |title=[Attempted suicide and alcohol dependence: results of an epidemiologic survey] |language=French |journal=Encephale |volume=24 |issue=4 |pages=347–54 |year=1998 |pmid=9809240 |month=July }}</ref> It has been found that drinking 6 drinks or more per day results in a sixfold increased risk of suicide.<ref name=behavioral_integrative_care>{{Cite book |last1= O'Donohue |first1=William T. |last2=R. Byrd |first2=Michelle |last3=Cummings |first3=Nicholas A. |last4=Henderson |first4=Deborah P. |title=Behavioral integrative care: treatments that work in the primary care setting |url=http://books.google.com/?id=PO5u2w3qL68C |year=2005 |publisher=Brunner-Routledge |location=New York |isbn=978-0-415-94946-0 |page= 115}}</ref><ref name=lexicon_of_psychiatry_neurology_and_neurosciences>{{Cite book |last=Ayd |first=Frank J |title=Lexicon of psychiatry, neurology, and the neurosciences |url= http://books.google.com/?id=ea_QVG2BFy8C |date=31 May 2000 |publisher=Lippincott-Williams Wilkins |location=Philadelphia |isbn=978-0-7817-2468-5 |page=256}}</ref> High rates of [[major depressive disorder]] occur in heavy drinkers and heavy drinking itself can cause [[major depressive disorder]] in a lot of alcoholics.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Fergusson DM, Boden JM, Horwood LJ |title=Tests of causal links between alcohol abuse or dependence and major depression |journal=Arch. Gen. Psychiatry |volume=66 |issue=3 |pages=260–6 |year=2009 |month= March |pmid=19255375 |doi=10.1001/archgenpsychiatry.2008.543 |url=http://archpsyc.ama-assn.org/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&pmid=19255375 }}</ref>
|-
! scope="row" | [[Benzodiazepines]]
| Chronic use or abuse of prescribed [[benzodiazepine]]s like Xanax, is associated with depression as well as increased suicide risk.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Neutel CI, Patten SB |title=Risk of suicide attempts after benzodiazepine and/or antidepressant use |journal=Ann Epidemiol |volume=7 |issue=8 |pages=568–74 |year=1997 |month=November |pmid=9408553 |doi=10.1016/S1047-2797(97)00126-9 |url=http://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S1047279797001269 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author=Taiminen TJ |title=Effect of psychopharmacotherapy on suicide risk in psychiatric inpatients |journal=Acta Psychiatr Scand |volume=87 |issue=1 |pages=45–7 |year=1993 |month=January |pmid=8093823 |doi=10.1111/j.1600-0447.1993.tb03328.x }}</ref> Depressed adolescents who were taking benzodiazepines were found to have a greatly increased risk of self harm or suicide.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Brent DA |title=Predictors of spontaneous and systematically assessed suicidal adverse events in the treatment of SSRI-resistant depression in adolescents (TORDIA) study |journal=Am J Psychiatry |volume=166 |issue=4 |pages=418–26 |year=2009 |month=April |pmid=19223438 |doi=10.1176/appi.ajp.2008.08070976 |url=http://ajp.psychiatryonline.org/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&pmid=19223438 |last12=Onorato |first12=M |last13=Kennard |first13=B |first14=TL |first15=LL |first16=JT |first17=M |first18=R |first19=H |last20=Porta |first20=G |last21=Keller |first21=MB |author-separator=, |author2=Emslie GJ |author3=Clarke GN |display-authors=3 |last4=Mayes |last5=Debar |last6=Mccracken |last7=Strober |last8=Suddath |last9=Leonard |first4=J. |first5=A. |first6=L. |first7=B. |first8=S. |first9=B. }}</ref> 
|-
! scope="row" | [[Cigarette smoking|Cigarettes]]
| There have been many studies showing a link between smoking, thinking about suicide and suicide attempts.<ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 15780776 | doi=10.1016/j.annepidem.2004.08.011 | volume=15 | issue=4 | journal = Annals of Epidemiology | year=2005 | title = Cigarette Smoking and Completed Suicide among Middle-aged Men: A Population-based Cohort Study in Japan | month=April | pages=286–92 | author=Iwasaki M, Akechi T, Uchitomi Y, Tsugane S}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 10800427 | volume=90 | issue=5 | journal = American journal of public health | year=2000 | title = Cigarettes and suicide: a prospective study of 50,000 men | month=May | pages=768–73 | author=Miller M, Hemenway D, Rimm E | pmc = 1446219 | doi=10.2105/AJPH.90.5.768}}</ref> In studies conducted among 50,000 nurses,and 300,000 male U.S. Army soldiers, those smoking between 1 to 24 cigarettes per day had twice the suicide risk; 25 cigarettes or more, 4 times the suicide risk, as compared with those who had never smoked.<ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 8427332 | volume=83 | issue=2 | journal = American journal of public health | year=1993 | title = Smoking and suicide among nurses | month=February | pages=249–51 | author=Hemenway D, Solnick SJ, Colditz GA | pmc = 1694571 | doi=10.2105/AJPH.83.2.249}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author=Thomas Bronischa, Michael Höflerab, Roselind Liebac |title=Smoking predicts suicidality: Findings from a prospective community study|journal=Journal of Affective Disorders
|volume=108 |issue=1 |pages=135–145 |year=2008 |month=May|pmid= 18023879|pmc= |doi= 10.1016/j.jad.2007.10.010 |url=}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 10873129 | volume=151 | issue=11 | journal = American Journal of Epidemiology | year=2000 | title = Cigarette smoking and suicide: a prospective study of 300,000 male active-duty Army soldiers | month=June | pages=1060–3 | author=Miller M, Hemenway D, Bell NS, Yore MM, Amoroso PJ}}</ref>
|-
! scope="row" | [[Cocaine]]
| Misuse of drugs such as [[cocaine]] often has a link with suicide. The time when the effects of a drug wear off is called "crash" or withdrawal phase. During this phase, many people feel bad. Suicide is most likely to occur during this phase in chronic cocaine-dependent users. Using more than one drug is more often linked with suicide in younger adults.  
|-
! scope="row" | [[Methamphetamine|Crystal meth]]
| Crystal meth use has a strong link with depression and suicide as well as a range of other adverse effects on physical and mental health.<ref name="Darke-2008">{{Cite journal | last1 = Darke | first1 = S. | last2 = Kaye | first2 = S. | last3 = McKetin | first3 = R. | last4 = Duflou | first4 = J. | title = Major physical and psychological harms of methamphetamine use | journal = Drug Alcohol Rev | volume = 27 | issue = 3 | pages = 253–62 | month = May | year = 2008 | doi = 10.1080/09595230801923702 | pmid = 18368606 }}</ref>
|-
! scope="row" | [[Heroin]]
| Deaths among heroin users attributed to suicide range from 3% to 35%. Overall, heroin users are 14 times more likely than their non-using peers to die from suicide.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Darke S, Ross J |title=Suicide among heroin users: rates, risk factors and methods |journal=Addiction |volume=97 |issue=11 |pages=1383–94 |year=2002 |month=November |pmid=12410779 |doi= 10.1046/j.1360-0443.2002.00214.x|url=http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/resolve/openurl?genre=article&sid=nlm:pubmed&issn=0965-2140&date=2002&volume=97&issue=11&spage=1383}}</ref> 
|}

====Problem gambling====
Problem gambling is often associated with increased [[suicidal ideation]] and attempts compared to the general population.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Moreyra, P., Ibanez A., Saiz-Ruiz J., Nissenson K., Blanco C. |title=Review of the phenomenology, etiology and treatment of pathological gambling |journal=German Journal of Psychiatry |volume=3 |issue= |pages=37–52 |year=2000 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |first1=Stefano |last1=Pallanti |first2=Nicolò Baldini |last2=Rossi |first3=Eric |last3=Hollander |chapter=11. Pathological Gambling |editor1-first=Eric |editor1-last=Hollander |editor2-first=Dan J. | editor2-last=Stein |title=Clinical manual of impulse-control disorders |url=http://books.google.com/books?id=u2wVP8KJJtcC&pg=PA251 |year=2006 |publisher=American Psychiatric Pub |isbn=978-1-58562-136-1 |pages=251–289}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author=Volberg, R.A. |title=The epidemiology of pathological gambling |journal=Psychiatric Annals |volume=32 |issue= |pages=171–8 |year=2002 }}</ref>

Early onset of problem gambling increases the lifetime risk of suicide, with gambling-related suicide attempts usually made by older people with gambling problems.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Kaminer Y, Burleson JA, Jadamec A |title=Gambling behavior in adolescent substance abuse |journal=Subst Abus |volume=23 |issue=3 |pages=191–8 |year=2002 |month=September |pmid=12444352 |doi=10.1080/08897070209511489 |url=http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/08897070209511489?url_ver=Z39.88-2003&rfr_id=ori:rid:crossref.org&rfr_dat=cr_pub%3dpubmed}}</ref> <ref name="autogenerated2003">{{cite journal | doi = 10.4088/JCP.v64n0908 | author = Kausch O | year = 2003 | title = Suicide attempts among veterans seeking treatment for pathological gambling | url = | journal = Journal of Clinical Psychiatry | volume = 64 | issue = 9| pages = 1031–8 | pmid = 14628978 }}</ref>Substance use<ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1016/S0740-5472(03)00117-X | author = Kausch O | year = 2003 | title = Patterns of substance abuse among treatment-seeking pathological gamblers | url = | journal = Journal of Substance Abuse Treatment | volume = 25 | issue = 4| pages = 263–70 | pmid = 14693255 }}</ref><ref>Ladd, G. T., Petry N. M. (2003) A comparison of pathological gamblers with and without substance abuse treatment histories. Experimental and Clinical Psychopharmacology, 11, 202-9.</ref> and mental disorders increase the risk of suicide in people with problem gambling.

===Medical conditions===
There is a link between suicidality and medical conditions, including chronic pain,<ref>{{cite journal |author=Ilgen MA, Zivin K, McCammon RJ, Valenstein M |title=Pain and suicidal thoughts, plans and attempts in the United States |journal=Gen Hosp Psychiatry |volume=30 |issue=6 |pages=521–7 |year=2008 |pmid=19061678 |pmc=2601576 |doi=10.1016/j.genhosppsych.2008.09.003 |url=http://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S0163-8343(08)00164-3}}</ref> mild brain injury, (MBI) or traumatic brain injury (TBI).<ref>{{cite journal |author=Simpson GK, Tate RL |title=Preventing suicide after traumatic brain injury: implications for general practice |journal=Med. J. Aust. |volume=187 |issue=4 |pages=229–32 |year=2007 |month=August |pmid=17708726 |url=http://www.mja.com.au/public/issues/187_04_200807/sim11240_fm.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author=Teasdale TW, Engberg AW |title=Suicide after traumatic brain injury: a population study |journal=J. Neurol. Neurosurg. Psychiatr. |volume=71 |issue=4 |pages=436–40 |year=2001 |month=October |pmid=11561024 |pmc=1763534 |url=http://jnnp.bmj.com/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&pmid=11561024 |doi=10.1136/jnnp.71.4.436}}</ref> The feelings of wanting to commit suicide lasted even after adjusting for depressive illness and alcohol abuse. In patients with more than one medical condition the risk was higher.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Druss B, Pincus H |title=Suicidal ideation and suicide attempts in general medical illnesses |journal=Arch. Intern. Med. |volume=160 |issue=10 |pages=1522–6 |year=2000 |month=May |pmid=10826468 |url=http://archinte.ama-assn.org/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&pmid=10826468 |doi=10.1001/archinte.160.10.1522}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author=Braden JB, Sullivan MD |title=Suicidal thoughts and behavior among adults with self-reported pain conditions in the national comorbidity survey replication |journal=J Pain |volume=9 |issue=12 |pages=1106–15 |year=2008 |month=December |pmid=19038772 |pmc=2614911 |doi=10.1016/j.jpain.2008.06.004 |url=http://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S1526-5900(08)00624-X}}</ref>

Problems with sleeping, such as [[insomnia]]<ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 22032872 | doi=10.1016/j.jad.2011.09.049 | title=Sleep problems outperform depression and hopelessness as cross-sectional and longitudinal predictors of suicidal ideation and behavior in young adults in the military | year=2011 | month=October | author=Ribeiro JD, Pease JL, Gutierrez PM, ''et al.'' | journal=J Affect Disord | volume=136 | issue=3 | pages=743–50}}</ref> and [[sleep apnea]] may be risk factors for depression and suicide. In some instances the sleep disturbance itself may be the risk factor independent of depression.<ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 16268383 | volume=28 | issue=9 | title=Suicidality and sleep disturbances | year=2005 | month=September | author=Bernert RA, Joiner TE, Cukrowicz KC, Schmidt NB, Krakow B | journal=Sleep | pages=1135–41}}</ref>

Many medical conditions can cause psychiatric symptoms. The major medical conditions which may cause psychiatric symptoms in order of frequency were infectious, pulmonary,<ref>Coffman K. Psychiatric issues in pulmonary disease Clin North Am. 2002 Mar;25(1):89-127. PMID 11912946</ref> thyroid, diabetic, hematopoietic, hepatic and [[Central nervous system|CNS]] diseases.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Hall RC, Popkin MK, Devaul RA, Faillace LA, Stickney SK |title=Physical illness presenting as psychiatric disease |journal=Arch. Gen. Psychiatry |volume=35 |issue=11 |pages=1315–20 |year=1978 |month=November |pmid=568461 |url=http://archpsyc.ama-assn.org/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&pmid=568461 |doi=10.1001/archpsyc.1978.01770350041003}}</ref>
Conservative estimates are that 10% of all psychological symptoms may be due to undiagnosed medical conditions,<ref>{{cite book |author=Morrison, James O. |title=When Psychological Problems Mask Medical Disorders: A Guide for Psychotherapists |publisher=The Guilford Press |location=New York |year=1999 |pages= |isbn=1-57230-539-8 }}</ref> with the results of one study suggesting that about 50% of individuals with a serious mental illness ''"have general medical conditions that are largely undiagnosed and untreated and may cause or exacerbate psychiatric symptoms"''.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Rothbard AB |title=Previously undetected metabolic syndromes and infectious diseases among psychiatric inpatients |journal=Psychiatr Serv |volume=60 |issue=4 |pages=534–7 |year=2009 |month=April |pmid=19339330 |doi=10.1176/appi.ps.60.4.534 |url=http://psychservices.psychiatryonline.org/cgi/content/full/60/4/534 |author-separator=, |author2=Blank MB |author3=Staab JP |display-authors=3 |last4=Tenhave |first4=T. |last5=Young |first5=D. S. |last6=Berry |first6=S. D. |last7=Eachus |first7=S.}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author=Hall RC, Gardner ER, Stickney SK, LeCann AF, Popkin MK |title=Physical illness manifesting as psychiatric disease. II. Analysis of a state hospital inpatient population|journal=Archives of General Psychiatry |volume=37 |issue=9 |pages=989–95 |year=1980 |month=September |pmid=7416911 |doi=10.1001/archpsyc.1980.01780220027002}}</ref>


